Interface Graph<NodeType,EdgeType,TransformerType>

Type Parameters:
NodeType - graph node type.
EdgeType - graph edge type.
TransformerType - transformer type. Transformer instances can be used to change the graph and its underlying representation to apply optimizations.
All Known Implementing Classes:
Cfg
public interface Graph<NodeType,EdgeType,TransformerType>

Directed graph abstraction for flow analysis. We specifically define all navigation methods in graph interface and do not ask nodes and edges to conform to any interface. This way graphs can be memory-efficient. The graph can have one or more incoming edges (i.e. edges, which end on some nodes in the graph, but originate somewhere outside the graph), and one or more outgoing edges.

transform

boolean transform(NodeType node,
                  TransformerType transformer)
Transforms the node with transformer. This will be called by solver to apply optimizations.

Returns:
true if there were changes made by transformer. While transformation should be always sound, it might be impossible to apply it in current context due to complexities of underlying structures. E.g. it is impossible to delete if statement test expression, while it is not evaluated if statement is not reachable. In this case transformer can return false and do no changes.
